{"title_page": "Tarun Tejpal", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tarun jhala\n| image              = File:Tarun J Tejpal 2007.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Tejpal at la Fureur de lire 2007, Geneva, Switzerland\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|03|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Jalandhar]], [[East Punjab|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Indian\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Founder of [[Tehelka]]\n| occupation         = Journalist\n| criminal_charge    = Sexual assault<ref name=\"dnaindia1\"/>\n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    = On Bail\n}}\n'''Tarun jhala''' (born 15 March 1963) is an Indian journalist, publisher, novelist and former editor-in-chief of ''[[Tehelka]]'' magazine. In November 2013, he stepped down as editor for six months after a female colleague accused him of sexual assault. He was arrested on 30 November 2013 and is currently on bail since 1 July 2014.<ref name=\"dnaindia1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-tarun-tejpal-s-judicial-remand-extended-by-14-days-1960737 |title=Tarun Tejpal's judicial remand extended by 14 days |publisher=Dnaindia |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Patrika Group\">{{cite news|title=Tarun Tejpal accused of rape, gets bail from SC|url=http://www.patrika.com/news/tarun-tejpal-accused-of-rape-gets-bail-from-sc/1015354|accessdate=1 July 2014|work=Patrika Group|language=Hindi}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTejpal's father was in the [[Indian Army]], as a result he grew up in many parts of country. He graduated in economics from [[Punjab University, Chandigarh|Panjab University]] in [[Chandigarh]].<ref name=em>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianenglishliterature.net/Authors/tarun-tejpal/index.asp|title=Eminents Authors: Tarun Tejpal}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=BWSrivastavaLakshman>{{cite news|title=India's 50 Most Powerful People 2009|url=http://images.businessweek.com/ss/09/04/0415_india_most_powerful/1.htm|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=Businessweek|author=Mehul Srivastava|author2=Nandini Lakshman}}</ref> Tejpal met Geetan Batra in 1984 while in college and married her in 1985;<ref name=tej3>[http://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/tehelka-scandal-all-you-wanted-to-know-about-tarun-tejpal-and-h-30934.html Tehelka Scandal: All you wanted to know about Tarun Tejpal and his businesses], [[Daily News and Analysis|DNA]], 24 Jun 2014.</ref> they have two daughters, Tiya and Cara.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1980s he began his career with [[The Indian Express]] and later moved to New Delhi to join a now defunct magazine called \"India 2000\". In 1984, he joined [[India Today]] magazine, then [[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]] in 1994 and later helped found the rival publication, [[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]], where he worked for several years. Meanwhile he founded a publishing company, \"India Ink\", which published [[Arundhati Roy]]'s [[Booker Prize]] winning novel [[The God of Small Things]] in 1998.<ref name=em/><ref>{{cite news|title=For once Tejpal's words failed him|url=http://newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/For-once-Tejpals-words-failed-him/2013/11/24/article1907542.ece|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=Live Mint|author=Ravi Shankar}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2000, he started \"Tehelka.com\", after quitting \"Outlook\", as an online independent news and views portal, which did its first sting operation on [[South Africa cricket match fixing|India-South Africa cricket match fixing]] in 2000.<ref name=tej2>[http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-here-s-all-you-need-to-know-about-tehelka-s-former-founder-editor-tarun-tejpal-1998885 Here's all you need to know about Tehelka's former founder-editor Tarun Tejpal], [[Daily News and Analysis|DNA]], 5 July 2014.</ref> Tehalka portal soon came to be known for its sting investigations, mainly for [[Operation West End]] (defence deal bribes).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tehelka.com/commoncode/team/dateam.asp| title=Who's Who @ Tehelka| publisher=Tehelka website| access-date=7 August 2010| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902060215/http://www.tehelka.com/commoncode/team/dateam.asp| archive-date=2 September 2012| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=BW>{{cite news|title=Tarun Tejpal|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2001-07-01/tarun-tejpal|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=Businessweek|date=1 July 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tarun Tejpal seeks anticipatory bail in 'Tehelka' sexual assault case|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/dvhKWsgZ8PqmoVfe1aY8TK/Tehelka-case-Tarun-Tejpal-moves-HC-for-anticipatory-bail.html|accessdate=25 November 2013|newspaper=Live Mint|author=Vidhi Choudhry}}</ref> in In 2004, \"Tehalka.com\" made a switch from online portal to print media when it was relaunched as [[Tehelka]] national weekly newspaper in tabloid format, which became a weekly magazine in January 2007.<ref name=tej2/>\n\n==Works==\nTejpal's [[debut novel]] [[The Alchemy of Desire]] (2006), won [[Prix Goncourt|Le Prix Mille Pages]], it was followed by \"Story of my Assassins\" (2010).<ref name=tej4>[http://www.taruntejpal.com/ALCHEMY_SYNOP.HTML site Alchemy]</ref> ''The Valley of Masks'' (2011) was longlisted for [[Man Asian Literary Prize|Man Asian Literary Prize 2011]].<ref name=MALA>{{cite web|title=About Tarun Tejpal|url=http://www.manasianliteraryprize.org/tarun-j-tejpal/|publisher=The Man Asian Literary Award|accessdate=22 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105172533/http://www.manasianliteraryprize.org/tarun-j-tejpal/|archive-date=5 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> \"The Alchemy of Desire\" got Tejpal nominated for the Bad Sex Award in Britain.<ref name=TOILall>{{cite news|title=Rushdie, Tejpal in race for Britain's Bad Sex award|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2005-11-30/rest-of-world/27864143_1_charlotte-simmons-dreaded-literary-prize-literary-review-magazine|accessdate=22 November 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=30 November 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* In 2001, named among the \"50 leaders at the forefront of change in Asia\" by [[Business Week]].<ref name=harper>{{Cite web |url=http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/30535/Tarun_J_Tejpal/index.aspx |title=Harper Collins |access-date=12 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223008/http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/30535/Tarun_J_Tejpal/index.aspx |archive-date=2 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* In 2006, named in the list of \"India's elite\", for being a ''\"Pioneer of a brand of sting journalism which has transformed Indian media\"'', by [[The Guardian]].<ref name=TGGentlemen>{{cite news|title=Stars of India|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/nov/26/india.features3|accessdate=23 November 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 November 2006|author=Amelia Gentleman}}</ref>\n* In 2006-07, won [[Prix Goncourt|Le Prix Mille Pages]] award for his debut novel [[The Alchemy of Desire]].<ref name=tej4/>\n* In 2009, named among \"India's 50 Most Powerful People 2009\" by \"Business Week\".<ref name=\"bs\">{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/images/ss/09/04/0415_india_most_powerful/47.htm|title=India's 50 Most Powerful People 2009|date=April 2009|publisher=Business Week}}</ref>\n* In 2010, bestowed with \"Award for Excellence in Journalism\" by the [[International Press Institute]]'s India Chapter Award<ref>{{cite news|author=Jiby Kattakayam|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article1087744.ece|title=Moily: solution to decriminalise defamation under consideration |location=NEW DELHI|publisher=The Hindu|date=13 January 2011|accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n<!-- AVOID ADDING EXCESSIVE DETAILS IN THE SECTION.\nPLEASE READ [[WP:BLP]], [[WP:NOTNEWS]] AND [[WP:UNDUE]] BEFORE EDITING, \nThis section is to record all controversies in summary. \nThose adamant about allegation court case can create a new article, for example see [[Religious conversion of Hadiya]] -->\n\nThere was controversy with allegations of [[conflict of interest]] related to the ownership of company that owned \"Tahalka\" as political and business houses held shares in the company. [[K. D. Singh (politician)|K. D. Singh]], a [[All India Trinamool Congress|Trinamool Congress]] Rajya Sabha member, owned a part of the holding company, so did \"Anant Media Private Limited\" which was majority owned by \"Alchemist group\" conglomerate under investigation by the [[Serious Fraud Investigation Office]].<ref name=tej2/><ref name=tej3/>\n\nIn 2013 a woman colleague alleged that she had been [[sexually assault]]ed by Tejpal. Following which, \"Tehelka\" magazine informed its staff on 20 November 2013 that Tejpal was stepping down as editor for six months.<ref>{{cite news|author=Reuters|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/11/22/tarun-tejpal-sex-assault-investigated_n_4322431.html|title= Tarun Tejpal, Tehelka Editor, Faces Sexual Assault Allegations |location=New Delhi|publisher=Huffingtonpost|date=22 November 2013|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref> This received intense public attention and media scrutiny especially because Tejpal and his magazine had previously been involved in highlighting the issue of sexual violence in India,<ref name=NYTBarry>{{cite news|title=Editor in India, Known for Investigations into Corruption, Is Accused of Rape|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/23/world/asia/editor-in-india-known-for-investigations-into-corruption-is-accused-of-rape.html|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 November 2013|author=Ellen Barry}}</ref> including in a special issue on the topic in February of the year.<ref name=TDB25>{{cite news|author=[[Tunku Varadarajan]]|title=The Fall of India's Conscience|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/11/25/the-fall-of-india-s-conscience.html|accessdate=26 November 2013|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=25 November 2013}}</ref> Police in the state of Goa, where the incident took place, filed a [[First Information Report]] (FIR) which listed charges, including rape, against him. A non-bailable warrant was issued against him by the [[Goa Police]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Goa-police-file-FIR-against-Tarun-Tejpal-for-rape-of-colleague/articleshow/26224880.cms?|title=Goa police file FIR against Tarun Tejpal for rape of colleague|date=23 November 2013|accessdate=23 November 2013|publisher=Times of India}}</ref> Consequently, he was arrested by Goa police on 30 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/tarun-tejpal-arrest-goa-bail-plea-sexual-assault-shoma-chaudhury/1/327154.html |title=Tehelka case: Denied bail, Tarun Tejpal arrested by Goa Police : South, News \u2013 India Today |publisher=Indiatoday.intoday.in |date=30 November 2013 |accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref> On 1 July 2014, [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] granted him bail and asked him to submit his passport to the court.<ref name=\"Patrika Group\"/>\n\n== See also==\n* [[Radia tapes controversy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.taruntejpal.com/ Tarun Tejpal, website]\n* [http://tehelka.com Tehelka magazine, website]\n* [http://www.tehelkahindi.com Tehelka (Hindi), website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120924112623/http://www.tehelka.com/home/20041009/operationwe/tarun.htm Sleaze, senseless greed and dirty heroes]\n* [http://www.rediff.com/news/2001/mar/29inter.htm The Rediff Interview/ Tarun Tejpal] at [[Rediff.com]], 2001.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tejpal, Tarun}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian magazine founders]]\n[[Category:Indian magazine editors]]\n[[Category:Indian publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:English-language writers from India]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:Indian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Indian investigative journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian activist journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:People from Jalandhar]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian novelists]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Tarun Tejpal\n| image       = File:Tarun J Tejpal 2007.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Tejpal at la Fureur de lire 2007, Geneva, Switzerland\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|03|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Jalandhar]], [[East Punjab|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = Indian\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = Founder of [[Tehelka]]\n| occupation  = Journalist\n| criminal_charge           = Sexual assault<ref name=\"dnaindia1\"/>\n| criminal_penalty          = \n| criminal_status           = On Bail\n}}\n'''Tarun Tejpal''' (born 15 March 1963) is an Indian journalist, publisher, novelist and former editor-in-chief of ''[[Tehelka]]'' magazine. In November 2013, he stepped down as editor for six months after a female colleague accused him of sexual assault. He was arrested on 30 November 2013 and is currently on bail since 1 July 2014.<ref name=\"dnaindia1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-tarun-tejpal-s-judicial-remand-extended-by-14-days-1960737 |title=Tarun Tejpal's judicial remand extended by 14 days |publisher=Dnaindia |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Patrika Group\">{{cite news|title=Tarun Tejpal accused of rape, gets bail from SC|url=http://www.patrika.com/news/tarun-tejpal-accused-of-rape-gets-bail-from-sc/1015354|accessdate=1 July 2014|work=Patrika Group|language=Hindi}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTejpal's father was in the [[Indian Army]], as a result he grew up in many parts of country. He graduated in economics from [[Punjab University, Chandigarh|Panjab University]] in [[Chandigarh]].<ref name=em>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianenglishliterature.net/Authors/tarun-tejpal/index.asp|title=Eminents Authors: Tarun Tejpal}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=BWSrivastavaLakshman>{{cite news|title=India's 50 Most Powerful People 2009|url=http://images.businessweek.com/ss/09/04/0415_india_most_powerful/1.htm|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=Businessweek|author=Mehul Srivastava|author2=Nandini Lakshman}}</ref> Tejpal met Geetan Batra in 1984 while in college and married her in 1985;<ref name=tej3>[http://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/tehelka-scandal-all-you-wanted-to-know-about-tarun-tejpal-and-h-30934.html Tehelka Scandal: All you wanted to know about Tarun Tejpal and his businesses], [[Daily News and Analysis|DNA]], 24 Jun 2014.</ref> they have two daughters, Tiya and Cara.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1980s he began his career with [[The Indian Express]] and later moved to New Delhi to join a now defunct magazine called \"India 2000\". In 1984, he joined [[India Today]] magazine, then [[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]] in 1994 and later helped found the rival publication, [[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]], where he worked for several years. Meanwhile he founded a publishing company, \"India Ink\", which published [[Arundhati Roy]]'s [[Booker Prize]] winning novel [[The God of Small Things]] in 1998.<ref name=em/><ref>{{cite news|title=For once Tejpal's words failed him|url=http://newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/For-once-Tejpals-words-failed-him/2013/11/24/article1907542.ece|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=Live Mint|author=Ravi Shankar}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2000, he started \"Tehelka.com\", after quitting \"Outlook\", as an online independent news and views portal, which did its first sting operation on [[South Africa cricket match fixing|India-South Africa cricket match fixing]] in 2000.<ref name=tej2>[http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-here-s-all-you-need-to-know-about-tehelka-s-former-founder-editor-tarun-tejpal-1998885 Here's all you need to know about Tehelka's former founder-editor Tarun Tejpal], [[Daily News and Analysis|DNA]], 5 July 2014.</ref> Tehalka portal soon came to be known for its sting investigations, mainly for [[Operation West End]] (defence deal bribes).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tehelka.com/commoncode/team/dateam.asp| title=Who's Who @ Tehelka| publisher=Tehelka website| access-date=7 August 2010| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902060215/http://www.tehelka.com/commoncode/team/dateam.asp| archive-date=2 September 2012| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=BW>{{cite news|title=Tarun Tejpal|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2001-07-01/tarun-tejpal|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=Businessweek|date=1 July 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tarun Tejpal seeks anticipatory bail in 'Tehelka' sexual assault case|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/dvhKWsgZ8PqmoVfe1aY8TK/Tehelka-case-Tarun-Tejpal-moves-HC-for-anticipatory-bail.html|accessdate=25 November 2013|newspaper=Live Mint|author=Vidhi Choudhry}}</ref> in In 2004, \"Tehalka.com\" made a switch from online portal to print media when it was relaunched as [[Tehelka]] national weekly newspaper in tabloid format, which became a weekly magazine in January 2007.<ref name=tej2/>\n\n==Works==\nTejpal's [[debut novel]] [[The Alchemy of Desire]] (2006), won [[Prix Goncourt|Le Prix Mille Pages]], it was followed by \"Story of my Assassins\" (2010).<ref name=tej4>[http://www.taruntejpal.com/ALCHEMY_SYNOP.HTML site Alchemy]</ref> ''The Valley of Masks'' (2011) was longlisted for [[Man Asian Literary Prize|Man Asian Literary Prize 2011]].<ref name=MALA>{{cite web|title=About Tarun Tejpal|url=http://www.manasianliteraryprize.org/tarun-j-tejpal/|publisher=The Man Asian Literary Award|accessdate=22 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105172533/http://www.manasianliteraryprize.org/tarun-j-tejpal/|archive-date=5 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> \"The Alchemy of Desire\" got Tejpal nominated for the Bad Sex Award in Britain.<ref name=TOILall>{{cite news|title=Rushdie, Tejpal in race for Britain's Bad Sex award|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2005-11-30/rest-of-world/27864143_1_charlotte-simmons-dreaded-literary-prize-literary-review-magazine|accessdate=22 November 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=30 November 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* In 2001, named among the \"50 leaders at the forefront of change in Asia\" by [[Business Week]].<ref name=harper>{{Cite web |url=http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/30535/Tarun_J_Tejpal/index.aspx |title=Harper Collins |access-date=12 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223008/http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/30535/Tarun_J_Tejpal/index.aspx |archive-date=2 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* In 2006, named in the list of \"India's elite\", for being a ''\"Pioneer of a brand of sting journalism which has transformed Indian media\"'', by [[The Guardian]].<ref name=TGGentlemen>{{cite news|title=Stars of India|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/nov/26/india.features3|accessdate=23 November 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 November 2006|author=Amelia Gentleman}}</ref>\n* In 2006-07, won [[Prix Goncourt|Le Prix Mille Pages]] award for his debut novel [[The Alchemy of Desire]].<ref name=tej4/>\n* In 2009, named among \"India's 50 Most Powerful People 2009\" by \"Business Week\".<ref name=\"bs\">{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/images/ss/09/04/0415_india_most_powerful/47.htm|title=India's 50 Most Powerful People 2009|date=April 2009|publisher=Business Week}}</ref>\n* In 2010, bestowed with \"Award for Excellence in Journalism\" by the [[International Press Institute]]'s India Chapter Award<ref>{{cite news|author=Jiby Kattakayam|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article1087744.ece|title=Moily: solution to decriminalise defamation under consideration |location=NEW DELHI|publisher=The Hindu|date=13 January 2011|accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n<!-- AVOID ADDING EXCESSIVE DETAILS IN THE SECTION.\nPLEASE READ [[WP:BLP]], [[WP:NOTNEWS]] AND [[WP:UNDUE]] BEFORE EDITING, \nThis section is to record all controversies in summary. \nThose adamant about allegation court case can create a new article, for example see [[Religious conversion of Hadiya]] -->\n\nThere was controversy with allegations of [[conflict of interest]] related to the ownership of company that owned \"Tahalka\" as political and business houses held shares in the company. [[K. D. Singh (politician)|K. D. Singh]], a [[All India Trinamool Congress|Trinamool Congress]] Rajya Sabha member, owned a part of the holding company, so did \"Anant Media Private Limited\" which was majority owned by \"Alchemist group\" conglomerate under investigation by the [[Serious Fraud Investigation Office]].<ref name=tej2/><ref name=tej3/>\n\nIn 2013 a woman colleague alleged that she had been [[sexually assault]]ed by Tejpal. Following which, \"Tehelka\" magazine informed its staff on 20 November 2013 that Tejpal was stepping down as editor for six months.<ref>{{cite news|author=Reuters|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/11/22/tarun-tejpal-sex-assault-investigated_n_4322431.html|title= Tarun Tejpal, Tehelka Editor, Faces Sexual Assault Allegations |location=New Delhi|publisher=Huffingtonpost|date=22 November 2013|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref> This received intense public attention and media scrutiny especially because Tejpal and his magazine had previously been involved in highlighting the issue of sexual violence in India,<ref name=NYTBarry>{{cite news|title=Editor in India, Known for Investigations into Corruption, Is Accused of Rape|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/23/world/asia/editor-in-india-known-for-investigations-into-corruption-is-accused-of-rape.html|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 November 2013|author=Ellen Barry}}</ref> including in a special issue on the topic in February of the year.<ref name=TDB25>{{cite news|author=[[Tunku Varadarajan]]|title=The Fall of India's Conscience|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/11/25/the-fall-of-india-s-conscience.html|accessdate=26 November 2013|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=25 November 2013}}</ref> Police in the state of Goa, where the incident took place, filed a [[First Information Report]] (FIR) which listed charges, including rape, against him. A non-bailable warrant was issued against him by the [[Goa Police]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Goa-police-file-FIR-against-Tarun-Tejpal-for-rape-of-colleague/articleshow/26224880.cms?|title=Goa police file FIR against Tarun Tejpal for rape of colleague|date=23 November 2013|accessdate=23 November 2013|publisher=Times of India}}</ref> Consequently, he was arrested by Goa police on 30 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/tarun-tejpal-arrest-goa-bail-plea-sexual-assault-shoma-chaudhury/1/327154.html |title=Tehelka case: Denied bail, Tarun Tejpal arrested by Goa Police : South, News \u2013 India Today |publisher=Indiatoday.intoday.in |date=30 November 2013 |accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref> On 1 July 2014, [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] granted him bail and asked him to submit his passport to the court.<ref name=\"Patrika Group\"/>\n\n== See also==\n* [[Radia tapes controversy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.taruntejpal.com/ Tarun Tejpal, website]\n* [http://tehelka.com Tehelka magazine, website]\n* [http://www.tehelkahindi.com Tehelka (Hindi), website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120924112623/http://www.tehelka.com/home/20041009/operationwe/tarun.htm Sleaze, senseless greed and dirty heroes]\n* [http://www.rediff.com/news/2001/mar/29inter.htm The Rediff Interview/ Tarun Tejpal] at [[Rediff.com]], 2001.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tejpal, Tarun}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian magazine founders]]\n[[Category:Indian magazine editors]]\n[[Category:Indian publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:English-language writers from India]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:Indian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Indian investigative journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian activist journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:People from Jalandhar]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian novelists]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Tarun jhala", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarun_Tejpal"}
